                    <tr>
                    <td><img src="/bullying/resources/images/dexter_the_tough_book.jpg" width="150" height="223" alt="Dexter the Tough cover"/></td>
                    <td><div class="listitem"><h3>Dexter the Tough</h3>
                    <p class="author">By Margaret Peterson Haddix </p>
                    <div class="orderfrom">Order From: <br />
                      <a href="http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Dexter-the-Tough/Margaret-Peterson-Haddix/9781416911708" class="externallink" target="_blank">Simon &amp; Schuster</a></div>
                    <p class="audience">Suggested Audiences: Grade 2 and older</p>
                    <p>It's only the first day of school for Dexter, but he's already mad at the principal, and the secretary, and the janitor, and the kids who laugh at him. When his teacher tells the class to write a story, Dexter writes about how tough he is -- and how he's already gotten into a fight. Is any of Dexter's story true? Why was the other boy crying before Dexter hit him? And why would the other boy still want to be Dexter's friend?</p>
