                                        <tr>
                    <td><img src="/bullying/resources/images/dancing_home_book.jpg" width="150" height="224" alt="Dancing Home cover"/></td>
                    <td><div class="listitem">
                      <h3>Dancing Home</h3>
                    <p class="author">By Alma Flor Ada and Gabriel M. Zubizarreta </p>
                    <div class="orderfrom">Order From: <br />
                      <a href="http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Dancing-Home/Alma-Flor-Ada/9781442481756" class="externallink" target="_blank">Simon &amp; Schuster</a></div>
                    <p class="audience">Suggested Audiences: Grade 3 and older</p>
                    <p>Mexico may be her parents&rsquo; home, but it&rsquo;s certainly not Margie&rsquo;s. She has finally convinced the other kids at school she is one-hundred percent American&mdash;just like them. But when her Mexican cousin Lupe visits, the image she&rsquo;s created for herself crumbles.</p>
                    <p>Things aren&rsquo;t easy for Lupe, either. Mexico hadn&rsquo;t felt like home since her father went North to find work. Lupe&rsquo;s hope of seeing him in the United States comforts her some, but learning a new language in a new school is tough. Lupe, as much as Margie, is in need of a friend.</p>
                    <p>Little by little, the girls&rsquo; individual steps find the rhythm of one shared dance, and they learn what &ldquo;home&rdquo; really means. In the tradition of My Name is Maria Isabel&mdash;and simultaneously published in English and in Spanish&mdash;Alma Flor Ada and her son Gabriel M. Zubizarreta offer an honest story of family, friendship, and the classic immigrant experience: becoming part of something new, while straying true to who you are.</p>
                    
